                    a(href='https://t.co/cUrtUsI40K') pic.twitter.com/cUrtUsI40K
                  | — Megan Reza (@megan_reza) 
                  a(href='https://twitter.com/megan_reza/status/917493603353554944?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw') October 9, 2017
                p A massive tower of smoke seen lingering over a Californian city.
                figure.figure
                  img.figure-image.img-fluid.rounded(src='/media/orangectyfr.jpg')
                  figcaption.figure-caption AP/CINDY YAMANAKA
                p State officials estimate the fires had burned about 115,000 acres over eight counties, and as of Tuesday, October 10th firefighters are still working to contain the relentless flames. Efforts of containment have been complicated by gusty winds, which spawned numerous secondary fires. 
                p This year has been particularly bad for wildfires, particularly in California. In the last decade 6 million acres were burned on average per year across America. In 2017, as of October 6th, we surpassed 8.5 million acres, almost a million of those acres burned in California alone. While this is very concerning, we haven’t surpassed the astonishingly high average of 2015. Although that is something to be grateful for, this year has been tormented by natural disasters, extending way beyond wildfires. And with the current administration seemingly doing everything it can to avoid hindering climate change, these disasters are going to become the norm.
